{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"74b29955-f9ea-4ccb-94ae-6702e7a80c75","content":"There's no workflow file in the current directory. Since this is a general question, here's what you need to change:\n\n### 1. **Configure NuGet.org**\nRegister your package for trusted publishing on [nuget.org](https://www.nuget.org):\n- Go to **Package → Manage trusted publishers**\n- Add a **GitHub Actions** publisher (owner, repo, optional workflow/environment constraints)\n\n### 2. **Update your workflow**\n\n**Add permissions** for OIDC token:\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # Required for OIDC\n  contents: read\n```\n\n**Replace** the `dotnet nuget push` step:\n```yaml\n# BEFORE (API key):\n- run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }} --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n\n# AFTER (trusted publishing):\n- run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n  env:\n    NUGET_AUTH_TOKEN: ''  # not needed anymore\n```\n\nActually, the simplest path is to use the **`dotnet nuget push` with `--api-key` sourced from an OIDC-exchanged token**. NuGet trusted publishing works like this:\n\n```yaml\njobs:\n  publish:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    permissions:\n      id-token: write\n      contents: read\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - uses: actions/setup-dotnet@v4\n        with:\n          dotnet-version: '8.0.x'\n      - run: dotnet pack -c Release\n      - name: Publish to NuGet (trusted publishing)\n        run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Key changes summary:\n| Step | What to do |\n|---|---|\n| **nuget.org** | Register GitHub repo as a trusted publisher for your package |\n| **`permissions`** | Add `id-token: write` to the job |\n| **`dotnet nuget push`** | Remove `--api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }}` — the OIDC token is exchanged automatically |\n| **Secrets** | You can delete the `NUGET_API_KEY` secret once verified |\n\nThe `dotnet` CLI (v8.0.4+) automatically detects the GitHub Actions OIDC environment and exchanges the token with NuGet.org — no API key needed. Make sure your `setup-dotnet` version is **v4+** to get this support.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"32a71319-2bca-4e5c-ae19-7773a7aa98f9","outputTokens":658,"requestId":"1C17:1E62:26618AF:2A4E0BA:69FBE327"},"id":"313262c4-c8e4-4fc0-9fd5-d6ef12d42556","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:56:21.126Z","parentId":"5bc4743c-2912-4593-b519-e68fb400ea55"}
